value.name: Why Is 137 the Most Magical Number? | HowStuffWorks
value.snippet: To physicists, 137 is the approximate denominator of the fine-structure constant (1/137.03599913), the measure of the strength of the electromagnetic force that controls how charged elementary particles such as the electron and muon interact with photons of light, according to the National Institute of Standards and Technology.

value.name: The Mysterious 137 – Richard Feynman - Ellenberger Architecture
value.snippet: The idea is quite simple, if you don’t use math to explain it. 137 is the odds that an electron will absorb a single photon. Protons and electrons are bound by interactions with photons. So when you get 137 protons, you get 137 photons, and you get a 100% chance of absorption. An electron in the ground state will orbit at the speed of light.

value.name: Why is the number 1/137 everywhere in physics? - Big Think
value.snippet: When you take its reciprocal (1 divided by that number), the result is about 137 (specifically, 137.035999084, again according to NIST).

value.name: 7 Secrets Why You Are Seeing 137 – The Meaning of 137
value.snippet: 137 is a bold expression of the auspicious and all-powerful master number 11 (the sum of the three numbers is 11). 137’s mystical features were realized in ancient times. The same powers this angel number had long ago are the same ones you experience today. In Physics, the number 137 is known as the fine structure constant.
